Creating an animated dash effect for arcs in a three.js globe using React involves working with three.js's materials and geometries, as well as integrating it into your React application. To achieve this, you'll also want to make use of the `react-three-fiber` (R3F) library which is a React renderer for three.js.

First, let's focus on setting up a basic three-globe using react-three-fiber, and then we'll proceed to add arcs with dash animation.

Here's a step-by-step guide to create the animated arcs on a globe within a React application. It assumes you have already set up a React project using Create React App and have installed the necessary dependencies.

1. **Install the necessary packages:**
   ```bash
   npm install three @react-three/fiber react-three-globe
   ```

2. **Create the ThreeGlobe component:**

   In your React component, you need to set up a three-globe and create a custom component to handle the arcs and their animation.

   ```jsx
   // ThreeGlobe.jsx
   import React, { useRef, useEffect } from 'react';
   import { Canvas, useFrame } from '@react-three/fiber';
   import { Sphere, Line } from '@react-three/drei';
   import * as THREE from 'three';

   function AnimatedArc({ start, end, color }) {
     // The arc geometry will be generated between two points
     const geomRef = useRef();
     const arcRef = useRef();

     useEffect(() => {
       // Create an arc curve between start and end points
       const startVec = new THREE.Vector3(...start);
       const endVec = new THREE.Vector3(...end);
       const curve = new THREE.Curve();
       curve.getPoint = t => {
         const vec = startVec.clone().lerp(endVec, t);
         vec.normalize().multiplyScalar(1 + 0.1 * Math.sin(Math.PI * t)); // elevate the arc
         return vec;
       };

       const points = curve.getPoints(50);
       geomRef.current.setFromPoints(points);

       // Initialize the dash with the line length
       const line = new THREE.Line(geomRef.current);
       const lineLength = line.computeLineDistances().lineDistances[1];
       arcRef.current.material.dashSize = lineLength;
       arcRef.current.material.gapSize = lineLength;
     }, [start, end]);

     useFrame(() => {
       if (arcRef.current) {
         // Update the dash offset to create the animation effect
         arcRef.current.material.dashOffset -= 0.02;
       }
     });

     return (
       <Line
         ref={arcRef}
         geometry={geomRef.current}
         points={[]}
         color={color}
         lineWidth={2}
         dashed={true}
         />
     );
   }

   function ThreeGlobe() {
     return (
       <Canvas>
         <ambientLight intensity={0.5} />
         <pointLight position={[10, 10, 10]} />
         // Add a simple sphere to represent the Earth   
         <Sphere args={[1, 64, 64]}>
           <meshPhongMaterial attach="material" color="royalblue" />
         </Sphere>
         <AnimatedArc start={[0, 0, 1]} end={[0.5, 0.5, 0.5]} color="white" />
       </Canvas>
     );
   }

   export default ThreeGlobe;
   ```

3. **Use the ThreeGlobe component:**

   Now, in your `App.js` (or any React component), you can import and use the `ThreeGlobe` component.

   ```jsx
   // App.js
   import React from 'react';
   import './App.css';
   import ThreeGlobe from './ThreeGlobe';

   function App() {
     return (
       <div className="App">
         <header className="App-header">
           <ThreeGlobe />
         </header>
       </div>
     );
   }

   export default App;
   ```

4. **Run your application:**

   Make sure your React application is running, and you should see a globe with an animated dash arc.

